{"title_page": "Aarogya Setu", "text_new": "{{short description|Mobile Application}}\n'''Aarogya Setu''' is a [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] tracking mobile application developed by the [[National Informatics Centre]] that comes under the [[Ministry of Electronics and Information Technology]], [[Government of India]].\n\n[[Image:Aarogya Setu.jpg|right|thumb|200px|The logo of Aarogya Setu app]]\n\n==Overview==\nThe stated purpose of this app is to spread the awareness and to connect essential health services to the people of India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/trends/coronavirus-pandemic-govt-launches-covid-19-tracking-app-aarogya-setu-for-android-ios-users-5101621.html|title=Coronavirus pandemic {{!}} Govt launches COVID-19 tracking app 'Aarogya Setu' for Android, iOS users|website=Moneycontrol|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />. This app will augment the initiatives of the [[Health department|Department of Health]] to contain the risks of COVID-19, and sharing the best practices and advisories. This is a tracking app which uses smartphone's [[Global Positioning System|GPS]] and [[Bluetooth]] features to track the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|coronavirus]] infection. Aarogya Setu app is available for [[Android (operating system)|Android]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=nic.goi.aarogyasetu&hl=en_IN|title=Aarogya Setu \u2013 Apps on Google Play|website=play.google.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> and [[iOS]] mobile operating systems<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mygov.in/aarogya-setu-app/|title=Aarogya Setu Mobile App|website=MyGov.in|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>. Using bluetooth technology, the Aarogya Setu app tries to determine the risk if one has been near a Covid-19 infected person (within six feet of distance) by scanning through a database of known cases across India, and using location information it determines the location one is in belongs to the infected areas based on the data available.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/technology/apps/govt-launches-aarogya-setu-a-coronavirus-tracker-app-all-you-need-to-know-11585821224138.html|title=Govt launches 'Aarogya Setu', a coronavirus tracker app: All you need to know|date=2020-04-02|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nThis app is an updated version of an earlier app called '''Corona Kavach''' (now discontinued) which was already released by the [[Government of India]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/industry/technology/govt-discontinues-corona-kavach-aarogya-setu-is-now-indias-go-to-covid-19-tracking-app/1919378/|title=Govt discontinues Corona Kavach, Aarogya Setu is now India\u2019s go-to COVID-19 tracking app|date=2020-04-05|website=The Financial Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Aarogya Setu crossed five million downloads within the three days of its launch, making it one of the most popular government apps in India<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gadgets.ndtv.com/apps/news/aarogya-setu-tops-india-charts-on-app-stores-5-million-installs-in-three-days-of-launch-coronavirus-2206060|title=Aarogya Setu App Crosses 5 Million Installs in 3 Days|website=NDTV Gadgets 360|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abplive.com/news/gadgets/coronavirus-india-govts-aarogya-setu-app-crosses-5-million-downloads-in-3-days-1189576|title=Coronavirus India: Govt's 'Aarogya Setu' App Crosses 5 Million Downloads in 3 Days|last=Bureau|first=ABP News|date=2020-04-04|website=news.abplive.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nAarogya Setu is available currently available in 11 languages<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aarogyasetu.in/|title=Aarogya Setu App|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> (English, Hindi, Telugu, Kannada, Malayalam, Tamil, Punjabi, Bengali, Oriya, Gujarati, and Marathi) and expected to be available in more Indian languages soon. One is asked to provide health and other profiling information after signing into the app. \n\nThe app is also built on a platform that can provide Application Programming Interface<ref name=\":0\" /> ([[Application programming interface|API]]) so that other computer programs, mobile applications and web services can make use of the features and data available of Aarogya setu.\n\n== Installation Process ==\n\n*First you have to download the App from Google play store or IOS store.\n*After Installing open the App and fill your basic information that requires.\n*# \n*#\n*# \n\n* Soon you will get an OTP, enter it and you are on.\n* Choose your gender from the options.\n* Enter your full name, age, and your profession, as app asked.\n* You'll be asked about your foreign travel history in last 30 days from the App. That's it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/tech/software/how-to-use-aarogya-setu-app-and-find-out-if-you-have-covid-19-symptoms/articleshow/75023152.cms?from=mdr|title=How to use Aarogya Setu app|last=|first=|date=|website=Economics Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> <br />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[COVID-19 apps]]\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|https://www.aarogyasetu.in}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n\n[[Category:Mobile applications]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in India]]\n[[Category:Software associated with the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2020 software]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Mobile Application}}\n'''Aarogya Setu''' is a [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] tracking mobile application developed by the [[National Informatics Centre]] that comes under the [[Ministry of Electronics and Information Technology]], [[Government of India]].\n\n[[Image:Aarogya Setu.jpg|right|thumb|200px|The logo of Aarogya Setu app]]\n\n==Overview==\nThe stated purpose of this app is to spread the awareness and to connect essential health services to the people of India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/trends/coronavirus-pandemic-govt-launches-covid-19-tracking-app-aarogya-setu-for-android-ios-users-5101621.html|title=Coronavirus pandemic {{!}} Govt launches COVID-19 tracking app 'Aarogya Setu' for Android, iOS users|website=Moneycontrol|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />. This app will augment the initiatives of the [[Health department|Department of Health]] to contain the risks of COVID-19, and sharing the best practices and advisories. This is a tracking app which uses smartphone's [[Global Positioning System|GPS]] and [[Bluetooth]] features to track the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|coronavirus]] infection. Aarogya Setu app is available for [[Android (operating system)|Android]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=nic.goi.aarogyasetu&hl=en_IN|title=Aarogya Setu \u2013 Apps on Google Play|website=play.google.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> and [[iOS]] mobile operating systems<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mygov.in/aarogya-setu-app/|title=Aarogya Setu Mobile App|website=MyGov.in|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>. Using bluetooth technology, the Aarogya Setu app tries to determine the risk if one has been near a Covid-19 infected person (within six feet of distance) by scanning through a database of known cases across India, and using location information it determines the location one is in belongs to the infected areas based on the data available.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/technology/apps/govt-launches-aarogya-setu-a-coronavirus-tracker-app-all-you-need-to-know-11585821224138.html|title=Govt launches 'Aarogya Setu', a coronavirus tracker app: All you need to know|date=2020-04-02|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nThis app is an updated version of an earlier app called '''Corona Kavach''' (now discontinued) which was already released by the [[Government of India]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/industry/technology/govt-discontinues-corona-kavach-aarogya-setu-is-now-indias-go-to-covid-19-tracking-app/1919378/|title=Govt discontinues Corona Kavach, Aarogya Setu is now India\u2019s go-to COVID-19 tracking app|date=2020-04-05|website=The Financial Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Aarogya Setu crossed five million downloads within the three days of its launch, making it one of the most popular government apps in India<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gadgets.ndtv.com/apps/news/aarogya-setu-tops-india-charts-on-app-stores-5-million-installs-in-three-days-of-launch-coronavirus-2206060|title=Aarogya Setu App Crosses 5 Million Installs in 3 Days|website=NDTV Gadgets 360|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abplive.com/news/gadgets/coronavirus-india-govts-aarogya-setu-app-crosses-5-million-downloads-in-3-days-1189576|title=Coronavirus India: Govt's 'Aarogya Setu' App Crosses 5 Million Downloads in 3 Days|last=Bureau|first=ABP News|date=2020-04-04|website=news.abplive.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nAarogya Setu is available currently available in 11 languages<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aarogyasetu.in/|title=Aarogya Setu App|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> (English, Hindi, Telugu, Kannada, Malayalam, Tamil, Punjabi, Bengali, Oriya, Gujarati, and Marathi) and expected to be available in more Indian languages soon. One is asked to provide health and other profiling information after signing into the app. \n\nThe app is also built on a platform that can provide Application Programming Interface<ref name=\":0\" /> ([[Application programming interface|API]]) so that other computer programs, mobile applications and web services can make use of the features and data available of Aarogya setu.\n\n== Installation Process ==\n\n#First you have to download the App from Google play store or IOS store.\n#After Installing open the App and fill your basic information that requires.\n## \n##\n## \n\n# Soon you will get an OTP, enter it and you are on.\n# Choose your gender from the options.\n# Enter your full name, age, and your profession, as app asked.\n# You'll be asked about your foreign travel history in last 30 days from the App. That's it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/tech/software/how-to-use-aarogya-setu-app-and-find-out-if-you-have-covid-19-symptoms/articleshow/75023152.cms?from=mdr|title=How to use Aarogya Setu app|last=|first=|date=|website=Economics Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> <br />\n== See also ==\n* [[COVID-19 apps]]\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|https://www.aarogyasetu.in}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n\n[[Category:Mobile applications]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in India]]\n[[Category:Software associated with the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2020 software]]\n", "name_user": "JamesJohn82", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aarogya_Setu"}
{"title_page": "Almir Kayumov", "text_new": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name  = Almir Kayumov\n| image = Almir Kayumov.jpg\n| fullname = Almir Izmailovich Kayumov\n| height = {{height|m=1.78|precision=0}}\n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=y|1964|12|30}}\n| birth_place = [[Moscow]], [[Soviet Union]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=y|2013|8|7|1964|12|30}}\n| death_place = [[Smolensk]], [[Russia]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| position   = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| youthyears1 =  \n| youthclubs1 =  \n| years1 =  1981\u20131987 \n| years2 =  1988\u20131989 \n| years3 =  1990 \n| years4 =  1991 \n| years5 =  1992 \n| years6 =  1993 \n| years7 =  1994\u20131995 \n| years8 =  1996 \n| years9 =  1997\u20131998\n| clubs1 =  [[FC Spartak Moscow]] \n| clubs2 =  [[FC SKA Rostov-on-Don]] \n| clubs3 =  [[FC Rotor Volgograd]] \n| clubs4 =  [[FC Spartak Moscow]] \n| clubs5 =  [[Kuopion Palloseura]] \n| clubs6 =  [[Daewoo Royals]] \n| clubs7 =  [[FC Lada Togliatti]] \n| clubs8 =  [[FC Dynamo-Gazovik Tyumen]] \n| clubs9 =  [[FC Neftekhimik Nizhnekamsk]]\n| caps1 =  48  \n| caps2 =  46  \n| caps3 =   5  \n| caps4 =   0  \n| caps5 =  26  \n| caps6 =  16  \n| caps7 =  50  \n| caps8 =  17  \n| caps9 =  38  \n| goals1 =  0  \n| goals2 =  0  \n| goals3 =  0  \n| goals4 =  0  \n| goals5 =  0  \n| goals6 =  0  \n| goals7 =  1  \n| goals8 =  0  \n| goals9 =  0 \n| nationalyears1 =   \n| nationalteam1 =  \n| nationalcaps1 =     \n| nationalgoals1 = \n| pcupdate = 4 October 2008 (UTC)\n| ntupdate =\n}}\n\n'''Almir Izmailovich Kayumov''' ({{lang-ru|\u0410\u043b\u044c\u043c\u0438\u0440 \u0418\u0437\u043c\u0430\u0439\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041a\u0430\u044e\u043c\u043e\u0432}}; 30 December 1964 \u2013 7 August 2013) was a [[Russia]]n [[football player]] and [[Referee (association football)|referee]].\n\n== Career ==\nKayumov played for [[FC Neftekhimik Nizhnekamsk]], [[FC Lada Togliatti]], [[FC Spartak Moscow|Spartak Moscow]], [[Rotor Volgograd]], [[SKA Rostov-on-Don]], in Russia, the [[Daewoo Royals]] in [[South Korea]], and [[Kuopion Palloseura]] in [[Finland]]. He played 6 games in the [[UEFA Cup 1986\u201387]] for FC Spartak Moscow.\n\nOn November 9, 2009, it was reported that Kayumov attempted to commit [[suicide]] by jumping out of his apartment window. Police negotiators talked him down, however, and he was brought to a [[psychiatric hospital]].<ref name=\"suicide\">{{Cite news | last = Wilson   | first = Jonathan   | title = Russian referee attempts suicide   | pages =    | newspaper = The Independent   | location = London   | date = 13 November 2009   | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/european/russian-referee-attempts-suicide-1819805.html | accessdate = <!-----13 November 2009----->}}</ref><ref name=\"russian suicide\">[http://www.interfax.ru/sport/news.asp?id=109556&sw=%EA%E0%FE%EC%EE%E2&bd=11&bm=10&by=2009&ed=11&em=11&ey=2009&secid=0&mp=0&p=1 \u0412 \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0435 \u043f\u044b\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0441\u044f \u043f\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0447\u0438\u0442\u044c \u0436\u0438\u0437\u043d\u044c \u0441\u0430\u043c\u043e\u0443\u0431\u0438\u0439\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\u043c \u0444\u0443\u0442\u0431\u043e\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0441\u0443\u0434\u044c\u044f \u041a\u0430\u044e\u043c\u043e\u0432]</ref> Kayumov later denied this, stating that he had just an ordinary treatment.<ref>{{cite web|date=November 19, 2009|url=http://www.championat.ru/football/news-355331.html|script-title=ru:\u041a\u0430\u044e\u043c\u043e\u0432: \u0432\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0438\u044f \u043e \u043f\u043e\u043f\u044b\u0442\u043a\u0435 \u0441\u0430\u043c\u043e\u0443\u0431\u0438\u0439\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u2014 \u0431\u0440\u0435\u0434!|publisher=Championat.ru|language=ru|accessdate=2009-11-29|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091122044603/http://www.championat.ru/football/news-355331.html|archivedate=22 November 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\n\nKayumov died on 7 August 2013, when he was hit by a [[GAZelle]] truck in [[Smolensk]]. According to investigators, his death was [[suicide]] as the surveillance camera footage showed that he jumped in front of the truck.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Gazeta.ru]]|url=http://www.gazeta.ru/sport/2013/08/07/a_5544869.shtml|script-title=ru:\u041f\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0431 \u0431\u044b\u0432\u0448\u0438\u0439 \u0444\u0443\u0442\u0431\u043e\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0430\u0440\u0431\u0438\u0442\u0440 \u0410\u043b\u044c\u043c\u0438\u0440 \u041a\u0430\u044e\u043c\u043e\u0432|language=Russian|date=7 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n* [[Soviet Top League]] champion: 1987.\n* Soviet Top League runner-up: 1984, 1985.\n* Soviet Top League bronze: 1986.\n* [[Soviet Cup]] winner: 1992.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{K League player}}\n* {{Soccerway referee|almir-kayumov/45460}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kayumov, Almir}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Russian footballers]]\n[[Category:Russian football referees]]\n[[Category:Soviet Top League players]]\n[[Category:FC Spartak Moscow players]]\n[[Category:FC SKA Rostov-on-Don players]]\n[[Category:FC Rotor Volgograd players]]\n[[Category:Busan IPark players]]\n[[Category:FC Lada Togliatti players]]\n[[Category:Russian Premier League players]]\n[[Category:FC Tyumen players]]\n[[Category:K League 1 players]]\n[[Category:Veikkausliiga players]]\n[[Category:Russian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Russian expatriate sportspeople in Finland]]\n[[Category:Russian expatriate sportspeople in South Korea]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Finland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in South Korea]]\n[[Category:Suicides in Russia]]\n[[Category:FC Neftekhimik Nizhnekamsk players]]\n\n\n{{Russia-footy-defender-1960s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name  = Almir Kayumov\n| image = Almir Kayumov.jpg\n| fullname = Almir Izmailovich Kayumov\n| height = {{height|m=1.78|precision=0}}\n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=y|1964|12|30}}\n| birth_place = [[Moscow]], [[Soviet Union]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=y|2013|8|7|1964|12|30}}\n| death_place = [[Smolensk]], [[Russia]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| position   = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| youthyears1 =  \n| youthclubs1 =  \n| years1 =  1981\u20131987 \n| years2 =  1988\u20131989 \n| years3 =  1990 \n| years4 =  1991 \n| years5 =  1992 \n| years6 =  1993 \n| years7 =  1994\u20131995 \n| years8 =  1996 \n| years9 =  1997\u20131998\n| clubs1 =  [[FC Spartak Moscow]] \n| clubs2 =  [[FC SKA Rostov-on-Don]] \n| clubs3 =  [[FC Rotor Volgograd]] \n| clubs4 =  [[FC Spartak Moscow]] \n| clubs5 =  [[Kuopion Palloseura]] \n| clubs6 =  [[Daewoo Royals]] \n| clubs7 =  [[FC Lada Togliatti]] \n| clubs8 =  [[FC Dynamo-Gazovik Tyumen]] \n| clubs9 =  [[FC Neftekhimik Nizhnekamsk]]\n| caps1 =  48  \n| caps2 =  46  \n| caps3 =   5  \n| caps4 =   0  \n| caps5 =  26  \n| caps6 =  16  \n| caps7 =  50  \n| caps8 =  17  \n| caps9 =  38  \n| goals1 =  0  \n| goals2 =  0  \n| goals3 =  0  \n| goals4 =  0  \n| goals5 =  0  \n| goals6 =  0  \n| goals7 =  1  \n| goals8 =  0  \n| goals9 =  0 \n| nationalyears1 =   \n| nationalteam1 =  \n| nationalcaps1 =     \n| nationalgoals1 = \n| pcupdate = 4 October 2008 (UTC)\n| ntupdate =\n}}\n\n'''Almir Izmailovich Kayumov''' ({{lang-ru|\u0410\u043b\u044c\u043c\u0438\u0440 \u0418\u0437\u043c\u0430\u0439\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041a\u0430\u044e\u043c\u043e\u0432}}; 30 December 1964 \u2013 7 August 2013) was a [[Russia]]n [[football player]] and [[Referee (association football)|referee]].\n\n== Career ==\nKayumov played for [[FC Neftekhimik Nizhnekamsk]], [[FC Lada Togliatti]], [[FC Spartak Moscow|Spartak Moscow]], [[Rotor Volgograd]], [[SKA Rostov-on-Don]], in Russia, the [[Daewoo Royals]] in [[South Korea]], and [[Kuopion Palloseura]] in [[Finland]]. He played 6 games in the [[UEFA Cup 1986\u201387]] for FC Spartak Moscow.\n\nOn November 9, 2009, it was reported that Kayumov attempted to commit [[suicide]] by jumping out of his apartment window. Police negotiators talked him down, however, and he was brought to a [[psychiatric hospital]].<ref name=\"suicide\">{{Cite news | last = Wilson   | first = Jonathan   | title = Russian referee attempts suicide   | pages =    | newspaper = The Independent   | location = London   | date = 13 November 2009   | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/european/russian-referee-attempts-suicide-1819805.html | accessdate = <!-----13 November 2009----->}}</ref><ref name=\"russian suicide\">[http://www.interfax.ru/sport/news.asp?id=109556&sw=%EA%E0%FE%EC%EE%E2&bd=11&bm=10&by=2009&ed=11&em=11&ey=2009&secid=0&mp=0&p=1 \u0412 \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0435 \u043f\u044b\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0441\u044f \u043f\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0447\u0438\u0442\u044c \u0436\u0438\u0437\u043d\u044c \u0441\u0430\u043c\u043e\u0443\u0431\u0438\u0439\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\u043c \u0444\u0443\u0442\u0431\u043e\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0441\u0443\u0434\u044c\u044f \u041a\u0430\u044e\u043c\u043e\u0432]</ref> Kayumov later denied this, stating that he had just an ordinary treatment.<ref>{{cite web|date=November 19, 2009|url=http://www.championat.ru/football/news-355331.html|script-title=ru:\u041a\u0430\u044e\u043c\u043e\u0432: \u0432\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0438\u044f \u043e \u043f\u043e\u043f\u044b\u0442\u043a\u0435 \u0441\u0430\u043c\u043e\u0443\u0431\u0438\u0439\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u2014 \u0431\u0440\u0435\u0434!|publisher=Championat.ru|language=ru|accessdate=2009-11-29|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091122044603/http://www.championat.ru/football/news-355331.html|archivedate=22 November 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\n\nKayumov died on 7 August 2013, when he was hit by a [[GAZelle]] truck in [[Smolensk]]. According to investigators, his death was [[suicide]] as the surveillance camera footage showed that he jumped in front of the truck.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Gazeta.ru]]|url=http://www.gazeta.ru/sport/2013/08/07/a_5544869.shtml|script-title=ru:\u041f\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0431 \u0431\u044b\u0432\u0448\u0438\u0439 \u0444\u0443\u0442\u0431\u043e\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0430\u0440\u0431\u0438\u0442\u0440 \u0410\u043b\u044c\u043c\u0438\u0440 \u041a\u0430\u044e\u043c\u043e\u0432|language=Russian|date=7 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n* [[Soviet Top League]] champion: 1987.\n* Soviet Top League runner-up: 1984, 1985.\n* Soviet Top League bronze: 1986.\n* [[Soviet Cup]] winner: 1992.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{K League player}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kayumov, Almir}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Russian footballers]]\n[[Category:Russian football referees]]\n[[Category:Soviet Top League players]]\n[[Category:FC Spartak Moscow players]]\n[[Category:FC SKA Rostov-on-Don players]]\n[[Category:FC Rotor Volgograd players]]\n[[Category:Busan IPark players]]\n[[Category:FC Lada Togliatti players]]\n[[Category:Russian Premier League players]]\n[[Category:FC Tyumen players]]\n[[Category:K League 1 players]]\n[[Category:Veikkausliiga players]]\n[[Category:Russian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Russian expatriate sportspeople in Finland]]\n[[Category:Russian expatriate sportspeople in South Korea]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Finland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in South Korea]]\n[[Category:Suicides in Russia]]\n[[Category:FC Neftekhimik Nizhnekamsk players]]\n\n\n{{Russia-footy-defender-1960s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "add referee link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Almir_Kayumov"}
{"title_page": "Marjatta Tapiola", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| name           = Marjatta Tapiola\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| birth_name     = Marjatta Tapiola\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1951|04|30}}\n| birth_place    = [[Sysm\u00e4]], [[Finland]] \n| death_date     = \n| death_place   =\n| nationality    = [[Finns|Finn]]\n| field          = Artist\n| training       = The Finnish Art Academy School\n| works          = \n| influenced by  = }}\n'''Marjatta Tapiola''' (born 30 April 1951, [[Sysm\u00e4]], [[Finland]]) is a [[Demographics of Finland|Finnish]] painter.<ref>ArtFacts.net, Marjatta Tapiola. URL: http://www.artfacts.net/en/artist/marjatta-tapiola-10443/profile.html (Referred 1 August 2013)</ref> At the time of her breakthrough in the 1980s the [[neo-expressionism|neo-expressionist]] art style was gaining popularity;<ref>Visit Helsinki, Marjatta Tapiola. URL: {{cite web|url=http://www.visithelsinki.fi/en/events-in-helsinki/marjatta-tapiola |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-08-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927081731/http://www.visithelsinki.fi/en/events-in-helsinki/marjatta-tapiola |archivedate=2013-09-27 }} (Referred 1 August 2013)</ref> however Tapiola's art does not necessarily fit inside these boundaries.<ref>Visit Helsinki, Marjatta Tapiola. URL: {{cite web|url=http://www.visithelsinki.fi/en/events-in-helsinki/marjatta-tapiola |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-08-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927081731/http://www.visithelsinki.fi/en/events-in-helsinki/marjatta-tapiola |archivedate=2013-09-27 }} (Referred 1 August 2013)</ref> Some typical elements in Tapiola's paintings are [[minotaur]]s, [[horses]] and [[skull]]s. Tapiola's newer paintings are said to be characterized by fluent drawing quality and multilayered lines.<ref>Piri-piri.fi, Fine Art. URL: http://www.piri-piri.fi/fine-art-hannu-vaisanen-tuomo-saali-marjatta-tapiola/ (Referred 2 August 2013) in English.</ref> Recent works often feature network of lines on a pale background.<ref>Piri-piri.fi, Fine Art. URL: http://www.piri-piri.fi/fine-art-hannu-vaisanen-tuomo-saali-marjatta-tapiola/ (Referred 2 August 2013) in English.</ref>\n\nIn February 2013 the portrait of the President of Finland, [[Sauli Niinist\u00f6]] painted by Marjatta Tapiola sparked controversy and got considerable media attention in Finland.<ref>Kaleva.fi (15 February 2013) Niinist\u00f6n muotokuvalle satelee kovaa kritiikki\u00e4. URL: http://www.kaleva.fi/uutiset/kotimaa/niiniston-muotokuvalle-satelee-kovaa-kritiikkia/621568/ (Referred 2 August 2013) in Finnish.</ref>\n\nMarjatta Tapiola has two daughters, writer ''Aina Bergroth'' (b. 1975) and film director and screenwriter ''Zaida Bergroth'' (b. 1977).\n\n==Early life==\nMarjatta Tapiola was born in 1951 in [[Sysm\u00e4]] which is a [[rural area]] in Finland.<ref>Kuvataiteilijamatrikkeli, Marjatta Tapiola. URL: http://www.kuvataiteilijamatrikkeli.fi/fi/taiteilijat/1449 (Referred 1 August 2013), in Finnish.</ref> Her father Olli Tapiola was a farmer and her mother Kerttu Tapiola was a housekeeper, [[art dealer]] and the owner of [[used bookstore]].<ref>Helsingin Sanomat, Kerttu Tapiola. URL: http://www.hs.fi/muistot/Kerttu+Tapiola/a1364352856219 (Referred 2 August 2013), in Finnish.</ref>\n\nTapiola studied in the Finnish Art Academy School (new name [[Academy of Fine Arts, Helsinki]]) between 1969\u20131974.<ref>Kuvataiteilijamatrikkeli, Marjatta Tapiola. URL: http://www.kuvataiteilijamatrikkeli.fi/fi/taiteilijat/1449 (Referred 1 August 2013), in Finnish.</ref> Her debut art exhibition was organized in year 1973 at [[Jyv\u00e4skyl\u00e4]], [[Finland]].<ref>Kuvataiteilijamatrikkeli, Marjatta Tapiola. URL: http://www.kuvataiteilijamatrikkeli.fi/fi/taiteilijat/1449 (Referred 1 August 2013), in Finnish.</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nMarjatta Tapiola has received several awards during her career. In 2004 she was awarded the [[Order of the Lion of Finland|Pro Finlandia]] medal.<ref>Kuvataiteilijamatrikkeli, Marjatta Tapiola. URL: http://www.kuvataiteilijamatrikkeli.fi/fi/taiteilijat/1449 (Referred 1 August 2013), in Finnish.</ref>\n\n*2006 Kuvataiteen valtionpalkinto\n*2005 H\u00e4m\u00e4l\u00e4is-Osakunnan kunniamerkki\n*2004 Pro Finlandia Prize\n*2004 Grant of the Finnish Cultural Foundation (in Finnish Suomen Kulttuurirahaston palkinto)\n*1981 Suomen Arvostelijain liiton Kritiikin kannukset 1980 Suomen Taideyhdistyksen Dukaattipalkinto\n\n==Literature==\n* Tapiola, Marjatta, Karvonen, Kirsti & Tiainen, Jussi: Marjatta Tapiola. Helsinki: Parvs Publishing, 2006. {{ISBN|978-952-5654-02-8}}.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://kokoelmat.fng.fi/wandora/w?si=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.muusa.net%2FE39.Actor_6DBFEFE3-7119-45B8-BC20-94C3A7B53E71&action=gen&lang=en&ifilter=images#listmod Works in the Finnish National Gallery]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tapiola, Marjatta}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Finnish painters]]\n[[Category:Pro Finlandia Medals of the Order of the Lion of Finland]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Lion of Finland]]\n[[Category:People from Sysm\u00e4]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| name           = Marjatta Tapiola\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| birth_name     = Marjatta Tapiola\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1951|04|30}}\n| birth_place    = [[Sysm\u00e4]], [[Finland]] \n| death_date     = \n| death_place   =\n| nationality    = [[Finns|Finn]]\n| field          = Artist\n| training       = The Finnish Art Academy School\n| works          = \n| influenced by  = }}\n'''Marjatta Tapiola''' (born 30 April 1951, [[Sysm\u00e4]], [[Finland]]) is a [[Demographics of Finland|Finnish]] painter.<ref>ArtFacts.net, Marjatta Tapiola. URL: http://www.artfacts.net/en/artist/marjatta-tapiola-10443/profile.html (Referred 1 August 2013)</ref> At the time of her breakthrough in the 1980s the [[neo-expressionism|neo-expressionist]] art style was gaining popularity;<ref>Visit Helsinki, Marjatta Tapiola. URL: {{cite web|url=http://www.visithelsinki.fi/en/events-in-helsinki/marjatta-tapiola |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-08-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927081731/http://www.visithelsinki.fi/en/events-in-helsinki/marjatta-tapiola |archivedate=2013-09-27 }} (Referred 1 August 2013)</ref> however Tapiola's art does not necessarily fit inside these boundaries.<ref>Visit Helsinki, Marjatta Tapiola. URL: {{cite web|url=http://www.visithelsinki.fi/en/events-in-helsinki/marjatta-tapiola |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-08-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927081731/http://www.visithelsinki.fi/en/events-in-helsinki/marjatta-tapiola |archivedate=2013-09-27 }} (Referred 1 August 2013)</ref> Some typical elements in Tapiola's paintings are [[minotaur]]s, [[horses]] and [[skull]]s. Tapiola's newer paintings are said to be characterized by fluent drawing quality and multilayered lines.<ref>Piri-piri.fi, Fine Art. URL: http://www.piri-piri.fi/fine-art-hannu-vaisanen-tuomo-saali-marjatta-tapiola/ (Referred 2 August 2013) in English.</ref> Recent works often feature network of lines on a pale background.<ref>Piri-piri.fi, Fine Art. URL: http://www.piri-piri.fi/fine-art-hannu-vaisanen-tuomo-saali-marjatta-tapiola/ (Referred 2 August 2013) in English.</ref>\n\nIn February 2013 the portrait of the President of Finland, [[Sauli Niinist\u00f6]] painted by Marjatta Tapiola sparked controversy and got considerable media attention in Finland.<ref>Kaleva.fi (15 February 2013) Niinist\u00f6n muotokuvalle satelee kovaa kritiikki\u00e4. URL: http://www.kaleva.fi/uutiset/kotimaa/niiniston-muotokuvalle-satelee-kovaa-kritiikkia/621568/ (Referred 2 August 2013) in Finnish.</ref>\n\nMarjatta Tapiola has two daughters, writer ''Aina Bergroth'' (b. 1975) and film director and screen writer ''Zaida Bergroth'' (b. 1977).\n\n==Early life==\nMarjatta Tapiola was born in 1951 in [[Sysm\u00e4]] which is a [[rural area]] in Finland.<ref>Kuvataiteilijamatrikkeli, Marjatta Tapiola. URL: http://www.kuvataiteilijamatrikkeli.fi/fi/taiteilijat/1449 (Referred 1 August 2013), in Finnish.</ref> Her father Olli Tapiola was a farmer and her mother Kerttu Tapiola was a housekeeper, [[art dealer]] and the owner of [[used bookstore]].<ref>Helsingin Sanomat, Kerttu Tapiola. URL: http://www.hs.fi/muistot/Kerttu+Tapiola/a1364352856219 (Referred 2 August 2013), in Finnish.</ref>\n\nTapiola studied in the Finnish Art Academy School (new name [[Academy of Fine Arts, Helsinki]]) between 1969-1974.<ref>Kuvataiteilijamatrikkeli, Marjatta Tapiola. URL: http://www.kuvataiteilijamatrikkeli.fi/fi/taiteilijat/1449 (Referred 1 August 2013), in Finnish.</ref> Her debut art exhibition was organized in year 1973 at [[Jyv\u00e4skyl\u00e4]], [[Finland]].<ref>Kuvataiteilijamatrikkeli, Marjatta Tapiola. URL: http://www.kuvataiteilijamatrikkeli.fi/fi/taiteilijat/1449 (Referred 1 August 2013), in Finnish.</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nMarjatta Tapiola has received several awards during her career. In 2004 she was awarded the [[Order of the Lion of Finland|Pro Finlandia]] medal.<ref>Kuvataiteilijamatrikkeli, Marjatta Tapiola. URL: http://www.kuvataiteilijamatrikkeli.fi/fi/taiteilijat/1449 (Referred 1 August 2013), in Finnish.</ref>\n\n*2006 Kuvataiteen valtionpalkinto\n*2005 H\u00e4m\u00e4l\u00e4is-Osakunnan kunniamerkki\n*2004 Pro Finlandia Prize\n*2004 Grant of the Finnish Cultural Foundation (in Finnish Suomen Kulttuurirahaston palkinto)\n*1981 Suomen Arvostelijain liiton Kritiikin kannukset 1980 Suomen Taideyhdistyksen Dukaattipalkinto\n\n==Literature==\n* Tapiola, Marjatta, Karvonen, Kirsti & Tiainen, Jussi: Marjatta Tapiola. Helsinki: Parvs Publishing, 2006. {{ISBN|978-952-5654-02-8}}.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://kokoelmat.fng.fi/wandora/w?si=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.muusa.net%2FE39.Actor_6DBFEFE3-7119-45B8-